The point of this meeting will be to understand how you can use R to manipulate and visualise data.

This will follow on from last weeks meeting in which we discussed R data types. In particular, we will focus on the data.frame type, and to an extent the matrix type.

While base R (i.e.R sans packages) has functionality for viewing and manipulating data types, we will use a package, dplyr, which provides succinct functions for working with dataframes as well as some other features which well discuss below.

Well begin by loading tidyverse and manipulating an R built-in dataset, mtcars, as an example.

Now well use dplyr to manipulate the data. dplyr is easy to use because its succinct, requiring little code compared to more hands-on base R methods. Lets filter the data based on miles per gallon.

mtcars$mpg %>% summary() ## get median, IQR, etc
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   10.40   15.43   19.20   20.09   22.80   33.90
mtcars %>% filter(mpg >= 22.80) ## get only entries in the top quartile
##                 mpg cyl  disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb

You probably havent seen one of the operators used above, %>%. This is the pipe symbol. Typically, R functions are written somewhat like an intransient sentence, with a function/verb and subject/dataset. The pipe symbol allows you to pre-specify the dataset and then pipe it to downstream functions without having to write them on sequential lines. For example, we can pipe the output from our filter function above to another filter function.

mtcars %>% filter(mpg >= 22.80) %>% filter(mpg < 30)
##                mpg cyl  disp hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Datsun 710    22.8   4 108.0 93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Merc 240D     24.4   4 146.7 62 3.69 3.190 20.00  1  0    4    2
## Merc 230      22.8   4 140.8 95 3.92 3.150 22.90  1  0    4    2
## Fiat X1-9     27.3   4  79.0 66 4.08 1.935 18.90  1  1    4    1
## Porsche 914-2 26.0   4 120.3 91 4.43 2.140 16.70  0  1    5    2

You can also assign the output.

mtcars_filtered <- mtcars %>% filter(mpg >= 22.80) %>% filter(mpg < 30)

You can also use dplyr to create new columns (mutate the dataframe) or remove existing columns, as shown below with a logical expression to determine whether entries in the mpg column are above or below the median.

mtcars %>% mutate(mpg_above_median = mpg > median(mpg)) %>% select(mpg_above_median, mpg) ## retain only mpg and mpg_above_median columns

While this is barely scratching the surface of dplyrs applications, it can also be used to create fast summaries of data. For example, we can summarise the median mpg of cars in the dataset grouped by the number of cylinders.

mtcars %>%
  group_by(cyl) %>% ## group the data
  summarise(median(mpg)) ## get the median mpg per group
## # A tibble: 3  2
##     cyl `median(mpg)`
##   <dbl>         <dbl>
## 1     4          26  
## 2     6          19.7
## 3     8          15.2

Being a popular data manipulation package, there are plenty of guides out there on how to use dplyr but I will direct you to this cheatsheet:

https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/data-wrangling-cheatsheet.pdf

Most of the time, we publish our data in plots rather than as raw data, so its helpful to understand how we make those plots. Most of our R plotting is done with another tidyverse package, ggplot2. To use this package to create a simple plot, you only need to specify three things: an x variable, a y variable, and a geom, basically a plot geometry such as a scatter plot, line plot, histogram, etc. The data itself is passed to ggplot2 through the ggplot function and the geom is added to the plot with an operator +. Ill give you a demo with the cars dataset.

ggplot(
  data = mtcars, ## what dataset the variables are in
  mapping = aes(x = hp, y = mpg) ## what variables to plot as x and y
) + geom_point() ## what geometry to use

You can stack multiple geometries into the same plot.

ggplot(
  data = mtcars,
  mapping = aes(x = hp, y = mpg)
) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() ## do both a scatter plot and a trend line
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

These are the core functions of ggplot. However, you can add additional information, such as categories by which ggplot can colour the data.

Now is also a good time to mention a data type we havent discussed, the factor class. Factors represent ordinal or categorical data. Here we will categorise the data according to the number of cylinders, which requires us to convert it from the numeric class to the factor class as shown below.

class(mtcars$cyl)
## [1] "numeric"
class(
  mtcars$cyl %>% as.factor()
  )
## [1] "factor"
ggplot(
  data = mtcars %>% mutate(cyl = as.factor(cyl)),
  mapping = aes(x = hp, y = mpg, colour=cyl)
) + geom_point()

You can also use continuous data as the x or y variable.

ggplot(
  data = mtcars %>% mutate(cyl = as.factor(cyl)),
  mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = mpg, colour=cyl)
) + geom_point()

Again, we can stack geometries on top of each other. Lets use a violin plot geometry.

ggplot(
  data = mtcars %>% mutate(cyl = as.factor(cyl)),
  mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = mpg, colour=cyl)
) + geom_violin() + geom_jitter(colour = 'black', width = 0.1) ## add some horizontal jitter for legibility

Finally, we can change the look of the plot. Each element including the background, text, axes, axis intervals, legend, title, etc. can be altered but for ease of use ggplot2 includes a number of pre-designed themes that will edit all of these at once in a single function.

ggplot(
  data = mtcars %>% mutate(cyl = as.factor(cyl)),
  mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = mpg, colour=cyl, fill=cyl)
) + geom_violin(alpha=0.25) + geom_jitter(colour = 'black', width = 0.1) +
  theme_classic()

To finish things off, lets plot some Seurat data. Seurat has its own plotting functions but they run on ggplot2 and we can add aesthetic features like we did with the plots above. For example:

library(Seurat)
## The legacy packages maptools, rgdal, and rgeos, underpinning the sp package,
## which was just loaded, will retire in October 2023.
## Please refer to R-spatial evolution reports for details, especially
## https://r-spatial.org/r/2023/05/15/evolution4.html.
## It may be desirable to make the sf package available;
## package maintainers should consider adding sf to Suggests:.
## The sp package is now running under evolution status 2
##      (status 2 uses the sf package in place of rgdal)
## Attaching SeuratObject
## load stroma
msc <- readRDS("/data/gpfs/projects/punim1236/spleen_st/Seurat_objects/Mueller_MSCs_old.rds")

## plot
DimPlot(msc, label=T)

## plot without bulky legend and axis text using the "theme" function
DimPlot(msc, label=T) + theme(
  legend.position = 'none',
  axis.text = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  axis.line = element_blank(),
  axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0.05),
  axis.title.y = element_text(hjust = 0.05)
)

We can also plot it with different aspect ratios, which helps with figure design.

## plot on a weird aspect ratio
DimPlot(msc, label=T) + theme(
  legend.position = 'none',
  axis.text = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  axis.line = element_blank(),
  axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0.05),
  axis.title.y = element_text(hjust = 0.05)
) + theme(
  aspect.ratio = 0.1
)

## plot with relative axis lengths
DimPlot(msc, label=T) + theme(
  legend.position = 'none',
  axis.text = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  axis.line = element_blank(),
  axis.title.x = element_text(hjust = 0.05),
  axis.title.y = element_text(hjust = 0.05)
) + coord_fixed()
